WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.340
 So the last topic we'll talk about here in object orientation is the notion of inheritance.

00:00:05.340 --> 00:00:11.820
 And this is a form of code reuse, and it's one of the more advanced aspects of object-oriented programming.

00:00:11.820 --> 00:00:16.400
 So just kind of understand what it is at a high level, and then you know where to come back to

00:00:16.400 --> 00:00:19.960
 when you need to learn a bit more about inheritance.

00:00:19.960 --> 00:00:23.820
 So the idea is, instead of making a new class from scratch,

00:00:23.820 --> 00:00:26.760
 we actually make a new class by starting with an existing class.

00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:31.320
 We are extending it, or another word for this is sub-classing.

00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:36.340
 And it's sort of a situation where you're like, I've got this code, and I've got this data,

00:00:36.340 --> 00:00:40.680
 and I just need to add a few things to it, and then I'll have a whole new thing.

00:00:40.680 --> 00:00:45.720
 And as you design objects and what we call object hierarchies, you often do this.

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:50.360
 And it's a form of sort of real clever code reuse.

00:00:50.360 --> 00:00:56.360
 But again, don't necessarily think that you're supposed to know when to use this or why to use this.

00:00:56.360 --> 00:01:00.220
 Right now, it's just terminology, okay, just terminology.

00:01:00.220 --> 00:01:02.740
 We have what call these as parent-child relationships.

00:01:02.740 --> 00:01:07.400
 The original class is called a parent, and the new class is called the child class.

00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:10.560
 So sub-classes are another word for this.

00:01:10.560 --> 00:01:12.640
 You have a class, and then you sub-class it.

00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:17.520
 I think extending and inheriting and parent-child are probably better ways of expressing it

00:01:17.520 --> 00:01:19.240
 than sub-classing.

00:01:19.240 --> 00:01:22.600
 So here's a bit of code, let's take a look at this.

00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:27.480
 This is, this code's unchanged, it's the party animal code that we've been saying all along.

00:01:27.480 --> 00:01:30.880
 It's the one that we construct and put a name in.

00:01:30.880 --> 00:01:32.800
 And now what we're going to do is extend it.

00:01:32.800 --> 00:01:36.760
 And so you'll notice that this code down here is the part that's doing the extending.

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:41.840
 So we're making a new class, football fan, and by putting in parentheses before the colon,

00:01:41.840 --> 00:01:47.160
 party animal, that says football fan inherits everything that is party animal,

00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:53.840
 meaning the X, the name, the init, the party, all those methods and data are sitting there.

00:01:53.840 --> 00:01:55.640
 And now we're going to add a new variable.

00:01:55.640 --> 00:01:59.840
 So football fan has, in addition to all those other variables, has points, and it has a

00:01:59.840 --> 00:02:01.760
 touchdown method.

00:02:01.760 --> 00:02:06.000
 And we add seven to the points, and then we call the party, and that does that.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:12.280
 So this is calling this method, because football fan includes X, name, and party, and init,

00:02:12.280 --> 00:02:15.120
 and everything, and all this, this constructor.

00:02:15.120 --> 00:02:20.520
 So this football fan is really an amalgamation of all these things together.

00:02:20.520 --> 00:02:24.340
 Party animal is just this stuff, right?

00:02:24.340 --> 00:02:25.800
 And so we still have two classes.

00:02:25.800 --> 00:02:26.880
 We don't just have one.

00:02:26.880 --> 00:02:29.180
 We didn't erase the party animal class.

00:02:29.180 --> 00:02:31.540
 And so we take a look at the code that we can run here.

00:02:31.540 --> 00:02:34.640
 We can say, oh, okay, let's make a party animal, sally.

00:02:34.640 --> 00:02:41.940
 And so that constructs an object like this, and then stores that in S, with an X starting

00:02:41.940 --> 00:02:50.040
 out at zero, and then we call S party, oops, better change that color, starts out at zero,

00:02:50.040 --> 00:02:53.560
 and then we call the party method, and that changes it to one, okay?

00:02:53.560 --> 00:02:59.480
 And so this bit of code, it's as if this part doesn't matter at all, because it is a party

00:02:59.480 --> 00:03:00.480
 animal.

00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:01.480
 It's not a football fan.

00:03:01.480 --> 00:03:09.240
 But now, if we take a look at this code down here, take this code down here, we're going

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:12.920
 to construct a football fan and pass in Jim.

00:03:12.920 --> 00:03:18.240
 So that actually uses the underscore knit from party animal, because we extended party

00:03:18.240 --> 00:03:19.760
 animal to make football fans.

00:03:19.760 --> 00:03:22.580
 So we inherited all of the good that was in there.

00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:27.040
 So there it's gonna make a name, a variable X, which is gonna start at zero, a variable

00:03:27.040 --> 00:03:32.080
 name that's gonna have Jim in it, and a variable points that's gonna have a zero in it.

00:03:32.080 --> 00:03:37.660
 So this J variable has more things in it than the S variable has.

00:03:37.660 --> 00:03:44.240
 And so we can call the J party, and if we call J party, that goes here and adds one

00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:45.240
 to X, right?

00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:51.420
 So that adds one to X, and then we call J touchdown, well, that comes down in here,

00:03:51.420 --> 00:03:54.780
 and adds seven to the points, right?

00:03:54.780 --> 00:03:56.760
 And then calls party within us.

00:03:56.760 --> 00:04:03.560
 And so self.party is the current object, i.e. self and J are the same thing, right?

00:04:03.560 --> 00:04:10.000
 Self.party, and then it goes up here and passes self in, and it adds one to the X, in this

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:12.120
 case of this J variable.

00:04:12.120 --> 00:04:19.560
 So this becomes two, and that's where it prints out seven and two, and away you go.

00:04:19.560 --> 00:04:26.640
 And so it's a way for you to kind of take all this stuff and stuff it into a class by

00:04:26.640 --> 00:04:31.660
 making a new class and just add the extending bits, the bits that are in addition to the

00:04:31.660 --> 00:04:32.740
 other stuff.

00:04:32.740 --> 00:04:39.620
 So like I said, inheritance is a powerful and wonderful concept, it's a form of, excellent

00:04:39.620 --> 00:04:47.440
 form of reuse, but basically the whole purpose of this lecture was so that I could in the

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:52.160
 future just use these words and you would understand them as compared to, I just want

00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:55.480
 to say method, and I've been saying method all along in this high time that I defined

00:04:55.480 --> 00:04:56.480
 it.

00:04:56.480 --> 00:04:59.020
 So let's just review one last time.

00:04:59.020 --> 00:05:04.420
 Class is a template, it is not actually a thing, it is a shape of a thing.

00:05:04.420 --> 00:05:07.640
 And we define it and say when we make one of these things, it's going to have these

00:05:07.640 --> 00:05:10.640
 variables in it, it's going to have these methods in it.

00:05:10.640 --> 00:05:16.320
 Attributes, variables within a class, method is a function that's inside of a class, object

00:05:16.320 --> 00:05:20.360
 is once we construct a class, we get back an object.

00:05:20.360 --> 00:05:25.680
 And so object here is the snowman cookies.

00:05:25.680 --> 00:05:28.480
 Class is the snowman cookie cutter.

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:35.740
 And a constructor is a bit of code that sets up our object, our instance, when it first

00:05:35.740 --> 00:05:37.160
 is created.

00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:42.680
 And inheritance is this ability to create a new class, but take all and import and affect

00:05:42.680 --> 00:05:46.500
 all the capabilities of an existing class.

00:05:46.500 --> 00:05:50.920
 So object-oriented is awesome.

00:05:50.920 --> 00:05:53.560
 For the rest of this class, we're not going to write any object code, we're not going

00:05:53.560 --> 00:05:57.340
 to use class at all, but we are going to use objects, and literally you've been using objects

00:05:57.340 --> 00:05:59.180
 from the beginning of this course.

00:05:59.180 --> 00:06:08.920
 As soon as you said print, whoops, as soon as you said x equals high, that's an object.

00:06:08.920 --> 00:06:14.880
 And as soon as you said x.upper, you were calling a method, right, you've been calling

00:06:14.880 --> 00:06:16.520
 a method all along.

00:06:16.520 --> 00:06:23.380
 When you're doing something like fh equals open, this thing you're getting back, that's

00:06:23.380 --> 00:06:30.040
 an object, and then you do fh.read or whatever, you're calling a method in the dot operator.

00:06:30.040 --> 00:06:32.140
 So you've been using objects all along.

00:06:32.140 --> 00:06:37.560
 I now am just finally explaining to you when I say call the read method or call the upper

00:06:37.560 --> 00:06:40.760
 method or what's this little dot and why is that there.

00:06:40.760 --> 00:06:47.200
 So again, it's time for us to understand that, but it will take you a long time before you

00:06:47.200 --> 00:06:52.860
 encounter a problem that's large enough where as part of your solution you're going to make

00:06:52.860 --> 00:06:53.920
 a new object.

00:06:53.920 --> 00:06:58.240
 But when you do, it's really a powerful thing.

00:06:58.240 --> 00:07:02.000
 It's a really bad idea for me as a teacher to say, oh, write a bunch of objects.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:03.520
 It's premature for that.

00:07:03.520 --> 00:07:08.720
 It's later is when you will actually learn how to use objects and you'll be like, oh,

00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:12.000
 thank heaven that these objects are here, okay?

